\begin_layout Title
Status consumption under wealth inequalities
\end_layout

\begin_layout Abstract

\shape italic
While status consumption is assumed to be ubiquitous, the possibility that
 extreme wealth inequalities in an economy could discourage status consumption
 has been explored less often.
 Using the context of a developing economy, we use a model that views status
 consumption as non-durable consumption in excess of the consumer needs
 relative to her wealth band and explore the opposing effects of peer influences
 and extreme wealth differences.
 Using consumption microdata from the Tanzanian LSMS survey for years 2010,
 2012 and 2014, we discuss how a segregation of status competitions based
 on extreme wealth differences and heterogeneity of available commodities
 could characterise status consumption in a developing economy.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Introduction
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Empirical studies in both developed and developing economies have associated
 social segmentation in an economy with disproportionate spending on conspicuous
 items 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "ChaiKaus2019,KausSA,ZahraIndia,JaikumarConspConIneq,FrieheGermany,heffetz_visibility"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 While such disparities are often explained with social-reference groups,
 the ways in which status consumption differ under the environment of extreme
 poverty in developing countries has been explored less often.
 Noting the prevalent wealth inequalities, we reexamine the notion of status
 in developing economies with a particular focus on the opposing direction
 of peer effects and the effects of wealth differences on status consumption.
 On one hand, status consumption is enhanced with peer effects but on the
 other, it would be discouraged under extreme wealth differences which the
 poorer consumer may not overcome.
 The relevance of pecuniary emulation - i.e.
 the notion that the habits of the rich are emulated by the poorer consumers
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "VeblenLeisureClass"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 - must therefore be considered warily as extreme wealth differences may
 have the effect of making status consumption appear futile to the poor
 consumers.
 Seeking conditions under which the demand for status goods is reduced in
 spatially or economically separated reference groups 
\begin_inset Foot
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
The terminology of goods vs commodities provided by Cramer 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "CramerIncomePrice1973"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 is used throughout the current chapter.
\end_layout

\end_inset

 we use a model for status consumption that views status in a context of
 wide wealth-band differences.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Treating wealth bands as relevant reference points in the empirical data,
 we argue that a consumer both compares herself with reference consumption
 of other groups which she doesn't belong and to those within her own group.
 Status consumption is relevant only to relative to a particular wealth
 band the consumers belongs to.
 This view of status consumption derives from a certain social-deference
 perspective for status that has been embraced in many economic studies
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "KoutsobinasStatusPoliticalEconomy,corneo_snobbism,ColemanSocialTheory1990"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 Status consumption from such a perspective is an attempt to offset the
 effects of existing wealth hierarchies towards status.
 Any two consumers in the model compete with each other for status using
 both the permanent ownership of items and the excess non-durable consumption
 (i.e.
 consumption above the cost of needs).
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The main goal of our empirical analysis is to understand the relative importance
 of differences in wealth at local levels to the wealth band differences
 observed at higher (national) levels.
 The empirical measurement of the permanent ownership of items uses the
 long term durable goods data available for every household in the survey.
 The excess non-durable consumption - which is defined with respect to a
 particular asset band (assessed with permanent ownership data) - is measured
 as excess over the cost of needs.
 The cost of needs used for excess in turn comprises of the cost of basic
 needs varying across regions and the cost of owning long-term goods that
 define the asset-band (costs associated with maintenance of long-term durable
 goods are also available in the survey).
 After adjusting for her needs, a consumer is meant to optimise the utility
 she obtains from both excess and long-term possessions.
 Social or spatial characteristics matter to the consumer in the model through
 both the durable goods cluster which the consumer belongs to and the price
 of needs that the consumer is exposed to.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In popular culture, status consumption often evokes images of wasteful expenditu
re and exclusive possessions that provide no economic value other than an
 attraction to people of equal affluence.
 We find this view rather inadequate for the utility provided by status
 consumption - which we believe is necessarily tied with social ranking.
 The view of status consumption as a waste presents an obvious issue with
 deciding whether a consumer's newly acquired wealth - whether it be jewelry
 of acquisition of undervalued land or property - is to be considered a
 part of her high-status necessities or wasteful conspicuous consumption.
 Since we have no way of knowing the intentions of consumers by evaluating
 their consumption diaries, we focus only on a comparison of consumption
 in excess of needs for a given set of measurements for existing  wealth
 and consumer's necessities.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This notion of excess excludes both the basic needs of the consumer as well
 as any maintenance costs for the long-term possession the role of which
 towards status is considered explicitly.
 Thus if one owns a car, the petrol used up for driving is not an excess
 and contributes only to the cost of bearing assets.
 As consumers are meant to use both excess and long-term ownership for status
 competitions and since excess varies according to a particular asset-cluster
 (band) 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathscr{A}$
\end_inset

 one belongs, the idiosyncratic habits average out for the notion of excess
 with respect to a wealth band 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathscr{A}$
\end_inset

.
 This is admissible since the empirical claim that we wish to test is whether
 non-durable status consumption - viewed as excess over needs - is dominated
 by status competition in the local wealth hierarchy or those among the
 consumers of similar wealth in a spatial proximity.
 The significance of the metrics related to wealth at local and national
 levels help us comment if local peer effects are more important for the
 consumer than the differences in wealth observed at a higher level in the
 wider economy.
 This perspective towards non-durable status consumption may be more relevant
 to how status motivations influence urban migration or demand for industrial
 items than the analysis of visible items in the economy.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The key appeal of the above approach is that unlike with the studies in
 visible consumption, one need not rely on the assumption that status goods
 are futile.
 While the futility assumption implicitly ensures the separability of demand
 for visible goods
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "HopkinsKornienkoStatusGames2004,ireland_signals"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 in an empirical analysis, it neither encompasses status consumption fully
 nor does it satisfy a desired criterion for visibility in bandwagon items
 such as electronics or cars that have clear utility in the regular sense
 apart from providing relative status advantage.
 The futility assumption may thus be inadequate for the representation of
 status consumption in a developing economy where both wealth differences
 and disparate economic conditions have a more conspicuous role to play.
 The notion of status using the permanent ownership and a more general notion
 of quality (which includes any high-price non-durable consumption) allows
 us to move beyond proxies of cultural contexts (e.g.
 using visibility surveys
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "heffetz_visibility,ZahraIndia"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 etc.) or a focus on historically restricted goods (e.g.
 ownership barriers for African American sub-population in the U.S., racial
 segregation in South Africa or religion-caste barriers in India 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "FrieheGermany,CharlesHurstRace,ZahraIndia"
literal "false"

\end_inset

) towards a generalised context of status consumption.
\end_layout

