\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Assisted with the developments in game theory and an improvement in the
 quality of microdata from consumption surveys, an interest in Veblen's
 observations has been revived in the recent decades (see Frank 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "FrankPond,FrankModel"
literal "false"

\end_inset

, Hirsch 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "HirschSocialLimits"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 and Koustobinas
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "KoutsobinasStatusPoliticalEconomy"
literal "false"

\end_inset

).
 This recent attention to status consumption need not to be viewed asunder
 from the consumer demand literature on habit-formation (see for example
 Muellbauer 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "MuellbauerRationalityMyopia1988."
literal "true"

\end_inset

's discussion of the myopia amongst consumers and Fisher-Shell
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "FisherShell1968"
literal "true"

\end_inset

 for the classical treatment of quality and cost-of-living indices).
 One could extend the notion of quality in consumption 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "NelsonQualityQuantity,GibsonKimQualityBog2019,DeatonQualityQuantityVariation"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 to view status consumption within the framework of consumed demand - as
 long as a suitable relation between consumption and status can be established.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The notion of status most commonly used in literature - where it is seen
 as a static long-term characteristics of the consumer - however presents
 an obvious paradox with respect to consumption since there cannot be any
 utility from status-consumption if status were only accumulated over a
 long-term.
 The admission that status is subject to change with consumption - just
 the way it is shaped by income or education - trivially resolves the paradox
 (see Michelson et al.
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "MichelsonMunizDeRose2013"
literal "true"

\end_inset

 and Psake et al.
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "PsakiSeidman2013"
literal "true"

\end_inset

 where status - like in many studies in sociology and health sciences -
 is used as a vector education or income ).
 We therefore use a dynamic view of status provided by Coleman
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "ColemanSocialTheory1990"
literal "true"

\end_inset

 and Corneo et al 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "corneo_snobbism"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 that has been widely embraced in the economic studies.
 The dynamic approach views status as a wealth-based ranking order that
 can be altered by the consumer with consumption.
 Thus a consumer achieves status utility through consumption with the hope
 and display of moving upwards in a ranking order that is otherwise determined
 by wealth.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We consider wealth bands the immediate reference group of the consumer where
 status consumption is observed.
 The context of wealth differences in status consumption has been explored
 less often in the literature on status consumption (except for some studies
 that explore the effect of income inequality on conspicuous consumption
 e.g.
 Jaikumar 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "JaikumarConspConIneq"
literal "false"

\end_inset

, Wisman 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "WismanSavingClassIdentity2009"
literal "false"

\end_inset

).
 The wealth-band based approach differs from the studies on visible consumption
 that explore the role of social identities in status consumption (see Chao
 et al.
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Chao1998"
literal "false"

\end_inset

, Charles et al.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "CharlesHurstRace"
literal "false"

\end_inset

, Omori et al.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "OmoriSmithVisRace"
literal "false"

\end_inset

, Kaus 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "KausSA"
literal "false"

\end_inset

and Khamis et al.
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "ZahraIndia"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 ; also see the marketing literature on identity formation and acquired
 goods
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "gierl_scarcity"
literal "false"

\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Eastman1999"
literal "false"

\end_inset

]).
 Particularly in the context of a developing country, we argue that the
 status-indicating goods need not be the same as those that are considered
 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

visible
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 in the developed economies.
 Instead the wealth differences - the necessary context of status consumption
 - may be far too wide for the limited visible items in the developing economies
 to matter.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Since the ranking of social characteristics is often a result of long-term
 asset inequalities, the role played by social identities towards status
 can also be viewed as part of wealth band hierarchy (see Timothy
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "TimothyBurkeLifebuoyMen1996"
literal "false"

\end_inset

, Srinivas
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "SrinivasSanskritization"
literal "true"

\end_inset

 for relevance of social identities; also see Frank
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "FrankPond"
literal "false"

\end_inset

, Bilancini et al
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "BILANCINIStatusRanking2012"
literal "false"

\end_inset

).
 However, such a treatment of social identities as wealth bands requires
 an empirical validation of the alignment of social identity difference
 with wealth inequalities.
 This is because the reference groups defined by social identities tend
 to limit the status consumption within themselves (see Chai et al
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "ChaiKaus2019"
literal "false"

\end_inset

).
 If aligned, the relevance of social characteristics for status consumption
 could also be understood in terms of the respective wealth bands that the
 consumers are a part of.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
For a given wealth band a consumer belongs to, status consumption consists
 of the consumer's long-term durable goods purchases and the excess non-durable
 consumption relative to her wealth band.
 The wealth bands are defined using the
\shape italic
 long-term possessions
\shape default
 of the consumer (the stock of durable goods possessed by consumer - inclusive
 of housing, land and other long-term assets) while the 
\shape italic
excess 
\shape default
non-durable consumption which help the perception of higher status is simply
 consumption in excess of needs in the wealth band.
 Evidently the fulfillment of basic needs itself does not offer an advantage
 to the consumer in a status competition - and a consumer with a habit of
 
\shape italic
relative 
\shape default
high-quality in consumption (or deriving higher felicity above the fulfillment
 of needs) measured as excess would have a higher status than another consumer
 with same needs who consumes less quality (excess).
 It follows that any status utility to be derived from non-durable consumption
 is constituted in the felicity from excess.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We use the costs associated with the durable goods and consumption in excess
 of a minimum necessary consumption to arrive at the empirical measurement
 of excess.
 The costs associated with the maintenance and upkeep of durable goods are
 easy to obtain as they are often available as part of the consumer diary.
 Similarly, the variation in the cost of a standard basket of basic needs
 across the regions and districts is often available with the market prices
 in a survey.
 Therefore, as long as the basic needs of the consumer and the possession
 of the long-term durable goods can be determined in an economy, the 
\shape italic
excess 
\shape default
can be readily estimated for the wealth band 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathscr{A}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A necessary requirement of this needs-based approach is that the empirical
 measurement of excess relies on the notion of what is 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

necessary
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 for the consumer (at least as much as it is for the very definition of
 conspicuous consumption
\begin_inset Foot
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
The Encyclopaedia Britannica definition of conscpicious consumption provides
 an illustrative instance of the role that empirical judgment plays in determini
ng consumer needs : 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

Conspicuous consumption ...
 describes and explains the practice by consumers of using goods of a higher
 quality or in greater quantity than might be considered necessary in practical
 terms
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "BritannicaConspCons2014"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\end_inset

).
 The very idea of basic needs can be controversial when on one hand, we
 have the view that needs are determined solely by subjective preferences
 (see Townsend
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "DoyalGoughNeeds1991"
literal "true"

\end_inset

) while on the other, a commonly-understood set of needs could supersede
 a consumer's subjective wants.
 To fix a particular definition of needs the analyses, we rely on both internal
 needs and external needs and lean towards an objective middle-path proposed
 by Doyal and Gough
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "DoyalGoughNeeds1991"
literal "true"

\end_inset

 who consider autonomy - in addition to health - as basic needs of the consumer.
 The needs of the consumer can thus be fixed without shunning the idea that
 the needs should vary across cultural contexts.
 We view basic (internal) needs of the consumer are requirements not meeting
 which would lead to a definite harm (this is in accordance to the theory
 argued for by Doyal and Gough 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "DoyalGoughNeeds1991"
literal "true"

\end_inset

).
 Such basic needs are easy to identify in the consumer dairy and are distinguish
ed from the costs (maintenance, fees etc.) associated with durable goods
 possessed by the consumer.
 To an argument that a family can survive on just starch, for example, the
 counter-argument would be that a foreseeable damage to the health of the
 consumer incurred by not having other nutrients is definite.
 A starch diet fulfilling the set of 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

basic
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 dietary needs can thus be ruled out.
 The role of basic needs in our empirical analysis designate the requirements
 the internal needs are common across all consumers regardless of their
 social context.
 The price of such basic needs is then calculated based on the market observed
 prices available in the survey.
 The costs associated with upkeep and maintenance of owned permanent assets
 are obtained directly from the survey.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The external needs of the consumer are included in the latter set of costs
 of associated with owned permanent goods.
 While the internal needs can be determined with the biological needs of
