\begin_layout Standard
Our empirical goal is to test the relative significance of the national
 level and local level of hierarchies with respect to excess.
 The two metrics we use for this purpose are:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate

\series bold
local relative-position 
\series default
(
\begin_inset Formula $LR$
\end_inset

) score - which is the ratio of wealth of the higher band to that of the
 consumer and represents local hierarchy for a consumer.
 The logarithm wealth of the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

higher band
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 for a consumer is the 
\begin_inset Formula $q^{th}$
\end_inset

 quantile of the logarithm of assets-value (AV) in the local area (determined
 with region and district) where 
\begin_inset Formula $q$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula $x\%$
\end_inset

 higher than the consumer's own logarithm AV rank.
 Thus with 
\begin_inset Formula $x=0.1$
\end_inset

 in a group of 100 consumers in a given area, a higher-band wealth for a
 consumer with 20% percentile local rank in log-AV would be the 30% quantile
 wealth in the area.
 
\begin_inset Formula $LR$
\end_inset

 score is essentially a local relative excpoverty metric - a higher 
\begin_inset Formula $LR$
\end_inset

 implies the consumer relative poverty with respect to the the richer neighbour.
 Being rich in a predominantly rich area would therefore result in a lower
 
\begin_inset Formula $LR$
\end_inset

 for a consumer than being poor in a rich neighbourhood.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
The 
\series bold
national relative-position
\series default
 (
\begin_inset Formula $NR$
\end_inset

) score - observes the same metric at a top-level i.e.
 across all consumers in the economy.
 The 
\begin_inset Formula $NR$
\end_inset

 metric thus represents the consumer's position in the national-level wealth
 hierarchy.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The relative important of above metrics help us comment if local peer effects
 are more important to the consumer than the wider-level wealth differences.
 If excesses depend weakly on difference wealth bands at the local level
 ( 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta A_{local}$
\end_inset

 ) but strongly on the national level difference (
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta A_{nat}$
\end_inset

