 is relatively separated from other regions.
 The local peer effects would thus drive excess consumption when excesses
 depend weakly on 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta A_{local}$
\end_inset

 but strongly on 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta A_{nat}$
\end_inset

 (this could happen either if the consumer  resides in a relatively rich
 region or in a relatively poor region).
 On the other hand, if we find a weak significance 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta A_{nat}$
\end_inset

 for excess but a stronger dependence of excess on 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta A_{local}$
\end_inset

, then separation exists at local levels i.e.
 the difference between rich and poor is significant at local levels.
 The rich consumer may therefore competing at a wider (national) level when
 the separation is strong at local levels (excess changes significantly
 across bands 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta A_{local}$
\end_inset

 but varies weakly across 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta A_{nat}$
\end_inset

 ).
 It is possible to have weak significance across both hierarchies - implying
 that excesses are not particularly separated at either levels or that there
 is strong dependence across both hierarchies - implying the consumers have
 their excesses within the limits of the position in the local hierarchies
 and are further separated by regional wealth at the wider levels.
 
\end_layout

