\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
For each wave of the survey, we use both the consumption diary of food items
 and the recall diary of non-food items to compute the cost of needs of
 the consumer - summing up the expenditure on the items that are considered
 necessities.
 The basic necessities comprise of food and energy - both of which appear
 in the weekly consumption diaries whereas energy and transport which contribute
d to cost of assets 
\begin_inset Formula $\Psi$
\end_inset

 appear in the monthly expenditure diaries.
 The cost of basic needs is the cost of minimal requirements for food and
 energy observed at the district level of consumer's residence.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The cost of basic needs therefore directly depends on the market-prices
 available in the survey for each locality.
 For example, within food category, we use the price of cheapest item in
 the set of minimum requirements for carbohydrates, fat, protein and fruits-vege
tables sub-categories observed at the district level.
 The cost of the minimal basket per head - composed of the recommended nutrient
 quantities - is calculated using the prices recorded in the survey and
 the number of members in the household.
 As it turns out, this minimum-cost basket for most regions (districts)
 is a selection of cassava, cooking-oil, eggs and bananas - the items that
 are cheapest items in every sub-category.
 The cost of the basket thus calculated is evidently much higher in the
 urban areas than in the rural areas (see Figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:BasketsRegions2010"

\end_inset

) .
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A similar treatment for energy category shows kerosene as the cheapest option
 for energy usage in most of Tanzania– partly due the sparsely available
 electricity in the country.
 With a calorie quota for lighting and the preparation of a typical meal
 (using the data on lighting and cooking available for every household in
 the survey), we infer the cost basis needs for energy using the recommended
 quantities of kerosene, charcoal and other energy sources (see Lam et al
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
