\begin_layout Standard
To establish that observing budget ratio 
\begin_inset Formula $w_{\nu}$
\end_inset

 is a measure for excess as appropriate as the amount spent towards excess
 that the consumers compete with - let’s consider three consumers - first
 of them is rich (with assets valued at 4,000,000), the second middle-income
 (assets valued at 900,000) and the third poor (assets valued at 10,000).
 Assuming the maintenance costs are simply 
\begin_inset Formula $\sqrt{A}$
\end_inset

 (for the value of asset 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

) and the cost of basic needs the same (
\begin_inset Formula $P_{\psi}\psi=200$
\end_inset

), the excess can be inferred as shown in the tables 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "tab:highwnu"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "tab:Lowwnu"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

.
 The consumer spending more on assets in Table 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "tab:Lowwnu"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 has a lower expenditure on excess and thus a lower 
\begin_inset Formula $w_{\nu}$
\end_inset

.
 If the rich in the example has both a higher excess and higher asset value
 then a separation is indicated applies and there can be no competition
 among the consumers.
 This is the state of the status competition in the Table 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "tab:Lowwnu"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

.
 On the other hand, if per-head excess of rich and poor consumers overlap
 we have less separation - as is the case in Table 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
