noprefix "false"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
To test the robustness of our measure of excess, we also use the subjective
 well-being data from the survey.
 If excesses are used to offset existing wealth hierarchies, we should find
 that those who are not satisfied with their financial status would have
 higher excess.
 Our empirical tests find that after accounting for wealth levels (durable
 goods ownership) those who are satisfied do have less recorded excess.
 That said, one cannot use this confirmation to decide whether a consumer
 has a higher excess due to not having a any options to purchase long-term
 assets or due to extreme peer pressures in her asset-band.
 This is once again due to the arguments we have discussed in the Section
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "subsec:Empirical-Method"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

.
 What we can ascertain however is that for the same total expenditure 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

, those with less assets consistently feel dissatisfied and have higher
 excess levels.
 The exceptions are indeed those extremely unsatisfied consumers who are
 also often extremely poor and have low excess.
 Similarly, extremely satisfied consumers in the higher asset band also
 have less excess.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Before we look into the fixed effects influencing the consumer's excess
 in more detail, consider how our conclusions on the variation of excess
 across wealth bands match up with the itemwise analysis which would have
 followed if the prices of individual items purchased were available in
 the survey.
 Consider an example where we have expenditure data on phones for a 1000
 families and we are able to determine that 200 of the 1000 consumers are
 rich, 400 are middle-income and the rest 400 are poor.
 Assume that we also have the data on their age and composition of the household.
 If we observe that some of them have much higher monthly expenditure on
 phones than others, then choosing 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

basic
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 expenditure on phone as the fees for landline, we may declare all expense
 higher than the landline costs as the excess.
 The argument that the individual’s communication needs are not down to
 landline costs is a valid one – considering that a consumer might have
 more family members living away, she may be conducting occupational calls
 using her phone or may simply be more talkative than others.
 Since we observe excess at the level of the wealth band however - such
 effects can be aggregated away and the effect of factors such as the number
 of family members, the regional effects etc.
 assessed.
 This is one reason why prices being observed locally is key to our analysis
 of excess as it proxies the regional differences in the economy.
 Had we used national level prices for calculating the costs of basic needs,
 the inferred excess at local levels would be rather meaningless.
 To sum up, as long as we can assume that landline is indeed a basic expense,
 we know how the excess varies in the population without a knowledge of
 the prices of every expensive phone variety.
 We can also conclude whether separation exists in the population of 1000
 families or not by observing if the excess is aligned with the observed
 bands 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathscr{A}$
\end_inset

 or not (i.e.
 if the consumers in the poorer band 
\begin_inset Formula $P$
\end_inset

 have consistently different excess from those in the richer band 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

).
 Such a conclusion is equivalent to the one whether the expenditure on particula
r types of phones is available in the survey.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
With the goal to decide the relative importance of local vs national wealth
 hierarchies, we use the 
\begin_inset Formula $LR$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $NR$
\end_inset

 metrics (representing the relative wealth of the individual in the region
 and that at the national level respectively) in the fixed-effects regression
 - using them as control variables along with 
\begin_inset Formula $log(P_{\psi})$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $log(x_{t})$
\end_inset

 .
 The dependent variables in the regression are 
\begin_inset Formula $w_{\nu},w_{A}$
\end_inset

.
 If a poor consumer who both has a low 
\begin_inset Formula $NR$
\end_inset

 but a high 
\begin_inset Formula $LR$
\end_inset

 score then we would conclude that she is in a poor region.
 Similarly, if she has high 
\begin_inset Formula $NR$
\end_inset

 score but low 
\begin_inset Formula $LR$
\end_inset

 score then she would be considered in a rich region.
 Further, if a separation is implied either locally or nationally - the
 competition with the richer consumer would be futile or impossible (a distincti
on that cannot be made by looking at the consumption data alone).
 In such a case when there is separation across wealth bands, lower excess
 is implied as the either of scores rise.
 The relative significance of the 
\begin_inset Formula $LR$
\end_inset

 score or the 
\begin_inset Formula $NR$
\end_inset

 score can tell us if the separation applies to the entire region (district)
 the consumer is a part or within her own community in the region where
 she resides.
 The 
\begin_inset Formula $LR$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $NR$
\end_inset

 metrics thus summarise the role of regional disparities towards consumption
 in the economy as well.
\end_layout

