\begin_layout Subsection
Discussion
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The purpose of our analysis had been to look beyond the models for visible
 consumption in an environment of uneven prices for excess consumption.
 This is motivated by the direct and dominant role played by the extreme
 differences in wealth and the segregation of quality of life in the developing
 countries.
 The variation in consumption above basic needs with respect to the distribution
 of durable goods in the economy views status consumption in a more general
 context.
 In the context of a developing country, when the majority of households
 have very little disposable income and durable goods possessions, the status
 consumption in the society would not be limited to the conventionally visible
 items e.g.
 clothing or jewelry alone.
 For example, the Tanzanian data shows that most houses report metallic
 sheet and bamboo/thatch roofs.
 In the backdrop of low durable goods ownership in an underdeveloped economy,
 a cement roof is likely to be more visible for signaling than would be
 the expenditure on clothing.
 The expenditure on carpets-rugs may seem to be a case of visible consumption
 at first - but its usage is more likely to be driven by asymmetries of
 home ownership rather than visibility needs of the consumers.
 The consideration of conventional visible goods e.g.
 clothing, shoes may therefore not provide us the desired view of how status
 may be signalled in the economy.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We also find that the effect of rural and urban differences on status consumptio
n is easier explained with the formulation of status consumption in terms
 of permanent ownership and excess.
 The explanation of how wide differences in wealth levels could affect consumer'
s the view of status consumption enhances our understanding how status competiti
ons may work under severe inequalities in more general settings.
 It is hoped that with the demand across different markets standardised
 with the suggested framework could help us understand factors that influence
 status consumption across the disparate variety of economies.
\end_layout

